e clear evidence that the fragment is a piece of marble in later re-use, and given the number of names that end in [---]νικα, it seems far more likely that this is a fragment of a funerary inscription from the second century CE or later.\u003C/p>  ",{"id":226,"html":227},"bibliography","\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> 49.1331.7 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Manganaro 1999 68-69 no.64 fig.146 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001813\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001813\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  ",{"id":229,"html":230},"handnote","\u003Cp>Deep, simply v-cut letters, with pronounced terminal serifs.\u003C/p> Line 1-2  19  Interlineation line 1 to 2  5-6  ",{"id":232,"html":233},"license"," Licensed under a Creative Commons-Attribution 4.0 licence.",[235,237,240,241],{"html":236},"Text encoding: Valentina Mignosa, Jonathan Prag; edition source: autopsy",{"id":238,"lang":130,"html":239},"edition-interpretive","\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]ΝΙΚΑ \u003Cbr id=\"al2-interpretive\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">2\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]ΣΑ \u003Cbr id=\"al3-interpretive\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">3\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">.\u003C/span>  \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>",{"html":236},{"id":242,"lang":130,"html":243},"edition-diplomatic","\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-diplomatic\">\u003Ca id=\"al1-diplomatic\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u00